Pairwise nucleotide and inferred amino acid comparison between strain B/03 and other MRV strains were performed for all ten segments (Table 2
). Nucleotide sequence alignments indicated that the L1, M1, M2, M3, and S1 genes from B/03 virus were highly related to those of WIV2–4 virus (98.63, 98.19, 97.04, 98.29, and 98.80%, respectively). The L2, L3 and S4 genes had highest identities (97.54–99.03%) with pig strains 729 and SC-A. The S2 segment of strain B/03 was most similar to strain MPC/04 on both the nucleotide and inferred amino acid level. Segment S3 of strain B/03 was most similar to strains HB-C and HB-A (isolated from minks) on both nucleotide and amino acid levels. The MRV S1 gene encodes the viral attachment protein σ1, which is unique to each MRV prototype strain and determines the serotype. When compared to the S1 sequences available in GenBank, the B/03 strain shares higher identity with that of MRV-1 than with those of MRV-2, MRV-3 or MRV-4 (Fig. 2
). Phylogenetic analysis of the L1, L2, L3, M1, M2, M3, S2, S3 and S4 genome segments for the B/03 strain and most related whole-genome strains available in GenBank is shown in Supplementary 1.
